  urldate = {2022-08-30},
  abstract = {This chapter presents mathematical examples and concepts that have proved extremely useful in resolving problems associated with navigation systems. The main part of the document assumes knowledge of linear differential equations and their solutions using state-space methods. The chapter presents examples of nominal trajectories and equations of motion and notation. It describes the principles involved in using the sensitivity coefficients to derive guidance laws. The success of most missions rests on whether the components and the manner in which they are used in the system can be chosen in such a way that the expected deviation from the desired objective at the end of the mission is within allowable bounds. On a space mission, the accuracy of the launch-vehicle guidance system contributes to the fuel requirements for a midcourse maneuver. The lower the accuracy of the guidance system, the larger the midcourse maneuver is likely to be. By appropriate usage of the sensitivity coefficients, one can relate each error source to some objective such as midcourse maneuver or miss at the target. In this manner, the tradeoffs between improvements in system design and objectives of the mission can be determined.},
